{"/service/ndnp/uuml/batch_uuml_nibali_ver01/data/sn83045396/print/1908061001/0821.xml":{"full_text":"HI i'\n.10 THE SALT LAKE TRIBUNE, WEDNESDAY MORNING,' JUNE 10, 1908.\nI)\nPleased With Business Outlook;\ni Condemns Political Agitation\nAgainst Railroads.\nBf j\nIjfj 1 4 Ji'AS COST SOUTHWEST\nl'- LINES ABOUT $5,000,000\nGeorge Left for Europe Tuesday\nR I -aiidWiU Attend Wedding\nII -j' of Anna.\nJ 1 NEW YOKK. .lime O. Before sailing\n'ior Europe on tlio steamer Prinr.es\nE sin Cecilie today, George J. Gould snid\nlie felt that in going away lie is leaving\nK 1 his properties in a comfortable position.\nI He expressed himself as modoratcb'\nr I optimistic\" on the general business\noutlook. In ill is connection he referred\nto tho earnings of the Western Union\nTelegraph company, which, ho snid, ho\nlooked upon as tho best criterion of\nI general, business, and said they are\nK showing a smaller ratio of decrease by\ncomparison with last. year. JIe said pp-K-\nlitical agitation against the railroads in\nII tho Southwest had made a difl'crcnee of\nI between $1,000,000 and 5.000,000 in\nt the net. earnings of tho Missouri Pa\nB cine, and added: \"Tho stockholders\n1 may figure out for themselves what this\nk means.\"\nft- Protected tho Wabash.\nI Referring to the troubles of tho\nE Wheeling Lake Erie and the Wabash\n1 Pittsburg Tenninal. Mr. Gould said:\nft \"The receivership for the Wheeling\nI Lake Erie was inevitable after the Wa\ntt bash-Pittsburg Terminal had defaulted,\nft; The Wabash-Pittsburg Terminal com\nK p:iny was, unfortunately, overcapital\nij ized. We probably could have carried\n1 it through, but T thought it was time\nf. to stop on behalf of the Wabash. The\nI Wabash is a fine property with great\nearning powers, and it will not be per\nf i mitted to become further involved.\"\nWill Attend Anna's Wedding,\nli; Asked if ho had abandoned any part\nr of his transcontinental railroad idea,\nf ,ii ilr. Gould said: \"Every 3-oungster has\nt t to have the measles and the whooping\nI f cough, and I don't know that they are\nf any the worse afterward.\"\nh. I ilr. Gould said the Wheeling Lako\nJ Erie receivership marked the end of the\nI j readjustments that -were necessary to\nj, bo made to his properties.\nII t Mr. Gould is quoted as having said: 1\nji f \"I expect to attend the wedding of\nmy sister, Auna Gould, to the Prince\nI Helie de Sagan. The marriage is to\nr take place with my consent and bless\nf ing and with the full consent of all\nI j the Gould family.\"\nIJ Jeffrey Also Talks,\njl NEW YORK, June 0. E. T. Jeffrey,\n(JSI' who is intimately familiar with the\nI various properties in the Gould system,\n.J said todav:\nI \"The $8,000,000 notes of Wheeling\n:fi Lake Erie Railroad company which ma-\nI ture.on August 1 will be prolected, but\n5 .iust how this will be done has not been\nf definitely decided. There arc still\nJj nearly two mouths in which to act upon\ni this matter. Regarding the future of\ni the \"Wheeling Lake Erie and Wabash-\ni Pittsburg Terminal, it may be stated\nin a general way that it has been de-\nI cided by the directors of both of the\nI companies that, the lines in the Gould\nfl system east of Toledo could be best\ndeveloped through a reorganization.\nThis will be brought about in due time,\ni but will not bo hurried.\"\nI! STATE AUDITOR'S REPORT\nSHOWS STATUS OF FUNDS\ni State Auditor .1. A. Edwards lias sub-\nr niltted to Governor Cutler the following:\nreport, showing1 the balunces In t lie\nvarious funds at tho close of business\nfor the six months ending May 31:\nGeneral fund 32.222.43\n1 University, principal 8,824.20\nf Agricultural college, principal.. 13.90r.40\nPublic buildings, principal 3.406.23\n1 Public buildings, Interest 1S.94C.23\nL( Reservoir, principal 49,214.70\nH Reservoir. Interest 3.0S3.61\nj r Insane nsyhim. principal 8.208.31\nk School of mines, principal 12.1fil.in\nf Deaf and blind, principal S.730.52\nP Reform school, principal 19.r.'.M.7fl\nI I Normal school, principal C.090.CG\nI Institution for the blind, prln-\nI I clpal 19.669.04\nI I Miners' hospital, principal 1G.1G9.G1\nI Miners' hospital. Interest 15.003.40\nf U, School land, principal.... S7.295.95\nI 1 School land, Interest 7.7-M.Of)\nli'i District school funds 18,294.08\nSheep Inspection fund 1.105. 14\nTrust fund 1.512.08\nRedemption fund 63.\"i.9r\nSuspense fund 8.01\n1 Forest reserve fund 15, 639. 36\nFish and game fund 13.110.30\nExtermination wild animals.'... 121.37\nI f 'Total 537S.3S5.81\nV, orrants outstanding May 31, 1908,\nI 51S.4D0.5C.\nk\ni I A. carload of Hood River strawberries.\n$4.50 per case. The best berrv to prc\nx serve, Lnned Grocery Company.\nHi SAMPLE\nI\n(1 Straws, soft and stiff, all\ni \"colors, $3.00 and $4.00 val-\nH ues choice, while they\nm. last aii3r hat in the house,\n$1 .6?\nSEE OCR WINDOWS.\n336 SOUTH MAli\nNear P. O.\nftftftB1\nTRAFFIC HESTQBEO 01\nTHE HORTHERN PACIFIC\n1\nPassengers Are Transferred fo\nHie Coast. Via the Oregon\nShort Line.\nBUTTE, Mont.. Juno 0. Tho first\nNorthern Pacific train from the Enst\narrived hero this morning. Butto is\nnow the terminus of tho road, and Ihc\npassengers aro transferred to tho coast\nvia the Oregon Short Liiro, as com\nmunication between this point and Mis\nsoula cannot be restored for about six\ndays.\nTho Great Northern may restoro com\nmunication between here and Grout\nPalls by Friday. General Manager\nGillie of the Amalgamated Copper com\npany said today that tho damage to tho\nBoston and Montanu smelters at Great\nFalls is not so heavy as was thought;\nthat so soon as ore can bo shipped, tho\nBoston and Montana mines here will re\nsume. General Manager Slade of the orth\neru Pacific is now here directing tho\nrepair work. Slado spent nil night on\nthe mountain top at Iloinestakc. and\nu ml or his master hand order is fast\ncoming out of chaos.\nBovond tho lnndslido to the east of\nthe citv lust night Butto has suffered\nno further damage, and today is bright\nand clear.\nNO EQUIPMENT FOR THE\nNORTH COAST LIMITED\nST. PAUL, June 0. For tho first\ntimo in mauy months tho North Coast\nLimited, the prido of tho Northern Pa\ncific railroad, failed to leave St. Paul\ntoday. The reason was two-fold. There\nwas \"no equipment with which to make\nup a train, most of it being stalled on\nthe wrong side of tho washout district\nin Montana and there being no prospect\nof getting a train through to Spokane,\nPortland and Seattle if a train had\nbeen made up.\nTn consequence all the passengers who\nwere to have taken the train were\ntransferred to the Northern Coast train,\nleaving about the same time. Accord\ning to reports received at the Northern\nPacific office today the entire valley\nof the Hell Gate river, between Mis\nsoula and Garrison. Mont., is reported\nunder water. Jt is understood that\nmost of the towns in the valley are\nflooded, and the people have boon com\npelled to take to the hills. No loss of\nlife has been reported.\nj RA5LROAD NOTES 1\nWestern roads arc said to be worried\nover the stubllty of the passenger rate\nsituation owing to tho disposition of cer\ntain lines to make concessions In order\nto secure excursion business and In\ncrease their revenues. It Is feared that\nbefore the summer Is ended many bad\nbreaks will occur.\nThe new Union Pacific bonds, the pros\npectuses of which were Issued today, were\nheld on the stock exchange In London\ntoday at a prcmum ranging from 1 to 1\nper cent. They closed at a premum of\nm\n\"Miners' day\" will be June 13. The\nRio Grande will run two special trains\nfrom Park City to ZIon that day and the\nminers of TIntIc will go to Spanish Fork\non the same road.\nSpecial rates of one fare for the round\ntrip from all parts of the State go Into\neffect on the HIo Grande on June 11,\ncontinuing until the 14th and good until\nthe 16th. This Is for the Y. M. M. I. A.\nexcursionists.\nS. V. Dcrrah, assistant general freight\nagent, and Superintendent Ilenger of the\nP.lo Grande visited Silver City Tuesday\nand made an Inspection of tho new Jesse\nKnight smelter there. The reduction\nworks will be opened sometime next\nmouth.\nV. 13. PInckney. general freight agent\nfor the \"Maple Leaf\" at Chicago, paid\nZlon a visit Tuesday.\n4\nGeneral Superintendent J. M. Davis of\nthe Oregon Short Line returned from\nMontana at noon Tuesday, having over\ncome the ravages of the floods on the\nnorthern section of the line.\nF. W. Gentsch, assistant to Superinten\ndent Lewis of the dining cars and hotels\non the Short Line system, with headquar\nters at Ogden. came to Salt Lake on\nbusiness Tuesday.\nA. T. Lewis, chief rate clerk of the\npassenger department of the Salt Lake\nRoute, with headquarters at Los Ange\nles, passed through the city Tuesday on\nhis way home. Mr. Lewis has been In\nChicago for the past three weeks, where\nhe attended the annual convention 6f the\nTranscontinental Pa.ssenger association,\nlie reports business In a great deal bet\nter condition than for some time past,\nand with prospects for a heavy travel\nWest this summer.\n1 INCORPORATIONS\nThe following companies filed articles\nof Incorporation in tho office of the sec\nretary of state Tuesday:\nRaven Mining company, of Xew Jer\nsey; capital stock. $2,000,000. in shares\nworth ?100. vIth $1,000 paid up: Incor\nporators, Ln-y D. Thomas, of Chicago:\nCharles N King and Lcgrand Bouker, of\nJersey City, X. J. A. D. Ferron Is the\nUtah agent.\nAlexis Mining company, of Provo; capi\nta) slock. 550.000. in shares valued at\nten cents; officers: John 13estclmcy.\npresident: George N\". Lawrenco. vice\npresident; Felix Bachman. secretary and\ntreasurer. The company will operate In\nthe Tintic district.\nThe Citizens' Investment company, with\na capital stock of $120,000, In $100 shares,\nfiled articles nf Incorporation In the of\nfice of tho county clerk Tuesday. The of\nficers arc- Dora B. Topham. president,\ntreasurer and general manager: M. M.\nWolfingor. vice president; C. 15. Haybould,\nsecretary. The company will conduct a\nreal estate and Investment business.\nPREPARE FOR CONVENTION\nOP PHARMACISTS AT PROVO\nAt the regular monthly meeting of the\nSalt Lako City Druggists association at\nthe. Commercial club, Tuesday night, the\nGreater part of the evening was devoted\nto a discussion of the coming annual\nState meeting of the Utah Pharmaceuti\ncal association at Provo, August 13 and\nH. At this meeting there will bo dele\ngates prufent from all o'er the Rocky\nMountain region and many Instructive\nand Interesting papers will be read.\nAlex Ilodqulst, president of tho asso\nciation, will be there, and It Is expected\nthat tho meeting will be of unusual profit.\nA number of results which have been of\nalmost Inesllmnblf benefit to the State\nhave been accomplish at these meetings\nIn the past, and it Ik expected that the\npresent one will prove to be no exception.\nThe social features of the affair will not\nbe neglected, and there will be manv la\ndles and members of the families of tho\nmembers of the association In attendance.\nJEFFREY TALKS IF\n9FSFFJIP;iFIC\nOne-Third of the Entire Line\nJs Now Absolutely\nCo m p I etc.\nTUNNELS HAVE BEEN\nREDUCED FROM 66 TO 44\nExpected That 800 Miles of\nRoacHVillBc Opened This\nSummer.\nAccording to a statement recently\nmade by i. T. JoTory, president of tho\nWcstorn Pacific, in New York, tho com\npany has already spent, over $30,000,000\nin construction, acquiring terminals and\nsecuring right of way. All the neces\nsary tenninal lands have, with unim\nportant exceptions, been secured. Grad\ning has been finished on GOO miles and\ntrack laid on about 300 miles. This\nmakes one-third of the rond absolutely\ncomplete.\nTho original plnns called for sixty\nsix tunnels with a total length of 02.\n014 feet, but these plans havo been re\nvised so that thoro will be only forty\nfour tunnels, with a total length of\n15,332 feet. About GO per cent of this\ntunnel work has boon completed.\nIt is expected that 300 miles of tho\nroad will be open for traffic this sum\nmer, and this will include tho line\nfrom Salt Lako to tho connection with\ntho Nevada Northern at Bows Siding\nand thus tn Kly. The entire line, 920\nmiles, will be in operation by this time\nnext year.\n1 REAL ESTATE NEWS\nTho sale of small lots for building con\ntinues active, according to tho reports\nof tho real estate dealers. Tuesday, the\nSalt J,akc Hoally Title company re\nported tho sale to Charles S. Burton of\ntwo tracts of land 10x174 and 2x20 rods,\nrespectively, at Sixth Kast and Ninth\nSouth streets, for Investment purposes.\nThe consideration was S6500. The tracts\nwill be subdivided Into small lots.\nBICYCLE EXCURSION TO OGDEN\nThursday, Juno 11, via O. S. L. Train\nleaves at G:lo p. in. Special returning\nleaves Ogden 11:00 p. in., after tho\nraces. A good list of events. Hound\ntrip $1.00.\nNOTICE.\nNotice Is hereby given by tho City\nCouncil of Salt Lake City of the Inten\ntion of such Council to make the fol\nlowing described Improvement, to wit:\nTo park. Improve and beautify both\nsides of Second avenue from Canyon road\nto Virginia street. In Parking District\nNo. 1, by removing from the curb to tho\nproperty lino all poor dirt or soli, gravel,\nrocks, roots and obstructions, and by\nplacing thereon loam, good soli, fertilizer\nand grass seed, and defray the abutters'\nportion of the cost and expense thereof,\nestimated at seventeen thousand three\nhundred sixty-two and 72-100 (517,362.72)\ndollars, or one and 11111-100000 ($1. 11111)\ndollars per front or linear foot of abut\nting property, there being 15.G2C.1G feet\nabutting said improvement, by a local\nassessment upon the lots or pieces ot\nground within tho following described\ndistrict, being the district to bo affected\nand benefited by said improvement,\nnamely:\nTho north side of lots 7, S, 9 and 10.\nblock 2, plat I; the north sldo of lots 3\nand 4, block 15; tho north sldo of lots\n3 und A, block 1G; tho north aldo of lota\n3 and 4, block 17; the north sldo of lota\n3 and 4. block 18; tho north side of lots\n3 and 4, block 13, the north side of lots\n3 and 4, block 20; tho north side of lots\n3 and 4, block 21; tho north sldo of lota\n3 and I, block 22; the north side of lots\n3 and 4. block 23; the north sldo of lots\n3 and 4, block 21; the north side of\nlots 3 and 4. block 25; tho north sldo of\nlots 3 and 4, block 2G; tho north t?lde of\nlots 3 and block 27; the north sldo ot\n?ots 3 and 4, block. 2S, plat D; tho north\nsldo of lots 3 and block 9; the north\nside of lots 3 and I, block 10, the north\nside) of lots 3 and 4, block 11; tho north\nside? of lots 3 und 4, block 12; the north\nside of lot? 3 and 4. block 13; the north\nsldo of lots 3 and 4. block 14; tho north\nslue of lots 3 and 4, block 15; the north\nside of lots 3 and 4, block 10, plat G;\npart of section 33, township 1 north,\nrango 1 east, abutting on tho east sldo\nof block 1C, part of section 33. township\n1 north, range 1 enst, abutting on the\neast side of block 17, plat G; the Bouth\nsldo of lota 1 and 2, block IS, the south\nside of 'ols I and 2. block 19; tho south\nsldo of lots 1 and 2, block 20; tho south\nside of lots 1 and 2, block 21; the south\nside of lots 1 and 2. block 22; the south\nside of lots 1 and 2. block 23; the south\nside of lots 1 and 2, block 24, plat G;\nthe south side of lots 1 and 2, block 29;\ntho south side of lota 1 and 2, block 30;\nthe south side of lots 1 and 2. block 31;\nthe south sldo of lota 1 and 2, block 32;\nthe south side of lots 1 and 2, block 33;\ntho south sldo of lots 1 and '2, block 34;\nthe south sldo of lots 1 and 2, block 35;\nthe south side of lots 1 and 2, block 3G;\nthe south side of lots 1 and 2, block 37;\ntho south side of lots 1 and 2, block 3S;\nthe south side of lots 1 and 2, block 39;\nthe south side of lots 1 and 2, block 40;\nthe south side of lots 1 and 2, block 41;\ntho south side of lots 1 and 2, block 42,\nplat D; the south side of lot3 1, 2. 3 and\n4, block 3. plat I; the south side of lots\n18 to 23. Inclusive. Victoria Place sub\ndivision, block 17, plat G. Salt Lake City\n.survey.\nAll protests and objections to the car\nrying out of such Intention must be pre\nsented in writing to tho City Recorder\non or before the 22nd day of June, 1903,\nbeing the llmo set by said Council when\nIt will hear and consider such protests\nand objections as may be mado thereto.\nBy order of tho City Council of Salt\nLake City. Utah.\nDated February 10. 190S.\n.1. 13. MOrtETON. City Recorder.\nParking Extension No. 2. cl33\nNOTICE\nOf Special Meeting or Stockholders of\ntho Castro Grecian Mining Company.\nA spucial meeting of the stockholders\nof the Castro Grecian Mining company\nwill be held at the office of said com\npany at room No. 59. Commercial block\nEast Second South street. Salt Lake City\nUtah, on the 19th day of June, 190S, at\nthe hour of U o'clock p. m. of said day\nfor tho purpose of amending the\" articles\nof Incorporation of said company. Tho\nnature of tho' proposed changes or amend\nments aro as follows:\n(1) To change the placo of organin\ntlon of said company, and the place of the\nGeneral offlco and principal place of bus\niness of said corporation from Salt Lake\nCity. Salt Lako county. Utah, to Ogden\nCity, Weber county, Utah.\n(2) To authoilzo and empower tho\nboard of directors of said corporation to\nsell, convey, lease, bond, mortgage or\nothorvlse dispose of any or all of' the\nproperty of said corporation, both real\nand personal, for such price end on such\nterms as to said board may seem for tho\nbest Interest of said corporation.\nJOHN COUTOS.\nPresident and Stockholder Representing\nMore Than One-Tenth of the Capital\nStock of the Castro Grecian Mining\nCompany.\nDated May 14, 1903. bl4G2\nji Miiiiiiiiii r mi\nYours at Last An Auto!\nBut What'H You Do With the Family Surrey\nBecause you can afford an auto it doesn't follow that you can afford to have a good\nfamily surrey or buggy standing in the shed as dead capital. You'd better convert it\ninto hard cash as quickly as you can. It may come in handy for repairs on the auto.\nAnd remember this: the longer it stands idle, the more the paint will peel, the more\nthe rust will corrupt, the shabbier it will look, and the cheaper you will have to sell it.\nAnother thing if you have a vivid memory of what you put out' for it, and don't want it to go as\ncharity by all means don't be compelled to sell it to your neighbors or your relatives. You'll get\nthe short end of it. They always expect a big discount on friendship. You'll be obliged to give it\nto them because they happen to know some of your little foibles and short comings.\nMake a business deal of it. Sell it to a total stranger who really wants it as badly as you want to get\nrid of it. You can make a deal with him that will be a bargain for both of you. Locate this stranger with a\nTRIBUNE WANT AD.\nA post card or telephone call will tell you that he is found. And take this with you whenever\nyou want to make an individual deal of any sort with a stranger you can always locate him with\na TRIBUNE WANT AD.\nASSESSMENT NO. 5.\nN'ephl Mining company, prlnclpa.' offlco\nroom C2 Commercial block. Salt Lako\nCity. Utah.\nNotice Is hereby given that at a meet\ning of tho board of directors of tho No\nphi Mining company, held on tho 13th\nday of May, 190S, an assessment of one\nhalf cent (Jc) per share was levied upon\ntho capital stock of said corporation,\npayable forthwith to G. M. Forbes, tho\nsecretary of the company, at No. 150\nWest Third South street. Salt Lako City,\nUtah.\nAny stock upon which this assessment\nmay remain unpaid on Thursday, tho lyth\nday of June. 190S. will bo delinquent, and\nwill bo advertised for salo at public auc\ntion, and unless payment Is mado beforo\nso many shares of each parcel of such\nstock as may be necoss'iry will bo sold\non the 9th dav of July. 190S, at 1 o'clock\np. m., of cald day, at 159 West Third\nSouth street, Salt Lako City. Utah, to\npay tho delinquent assessments thereon,\ntogether with tho cosl3 of advertising\nand expenses of sale.\nG. M. FORBES.\nSecretarv Ncphl Mining company. 159\nWest Third South street. Salt Lake City.\nDated this nth day of May. 1908.\nhl-U5\nASSESSMENT NO. 4.\nMountain Dell Consolidated Mln'flt:\ncompany: principal place of business. 2S1\nCity and County building. Salt Lako\nCity. Utah.\nNotice Is hereby given that at a meeting\nof the board of trustees of the Mountain\nDell Consolidated Mining company, hold\non the 19th day of May, 190S, an assess\nment of two (2) cents per share was\nlevied and assessed on tho capital stock\nof said corporation, payable at the of\nflco of H. W. Griffith, secretary of said\ncompany, at room 251 City and County\nbuilding. Salt Lake City, Utah, on or\nbeforo tho 24th day of June, 1908.\nAny stock upon which said assessment\nmay remain unpaid on the said 24th day\nof June, 190S, will bo delinquent and\nadvertised for salo at public auction, and\nunless payment 5s mado before, will be\nsold on tho 13th day of July, 1908, at 2:30\no'clock p. m. of said dy, to pay the said\ndelinquent assessment thereon, together\nwith the costs of advertising and ex\npenses of sale. II. W. GRIFFITH.\nSecretary.\n251 City mid County building,\nbait Lake City, Utah.\nb20Cl\nASSESSMENT NOTICE.\nRainbow Mining Company of Utah.\nPrincipal place of business. No. 32\nSouth Main street. Salt Lake City. Utah.\nNotice Is hereby given that at a meet\ning of tha board of directors of the Rain\nbow Mining company held on May 23.\n1908. an assessment of one-eighth\ncent per sharo was levied and assessed\non the capital stock of said corporation,\npayable on or beforo July I. 1908, to Er\nnest M. Fowler, secretary nnd treasurer\nof tho company, at the office of tho com\npany, No. 32 South Alain street. Salt\nLako City. Utah.\nAny stock upon which said assessment\nshall rclnaln unpaid on the said 1st day\nof July. 190S. will bo delinquent and ad\nvertised for sale at public auction, and.\nunless payment Is made before, will bo\nsold on August I. UI0S, at 1 o'clock p. m.\nof said day, to pay tho delinquent as\nsessment thereon, togethor with the coat\nof advertising nnd expense of sale.\nKRNEST M FOWLER,\nSecretary and Treaauror.\nOIlce No. 32 South Main street. Salt\nLake City. Utah. h2741\nNOTIOE OF ASSESSMENT NO. 13.\nButler-Llbcral Consolidated Mining\ncompany. Principal place of business,\n30G Auerboch building, Salt Lake City,\nUtah.\nNotice Is horeby given that at a meet\ning of the directors, hold on tho Sth day\nof June. 190S. an assessment of two\n(2) cents per share was levied on tho i\ncapital stock of the corporation, payable\nImmediately to C, 13. Oliver, secrotarv, at\ntho otllco of the company. 30tl Auerbach\nbuilding. Salt. Lako City. Utah.\nAny stock upon which this assesomcnt\nmay remain unpaid on Friday, July 17,\n1908, will bo delinquent and advertised\nfor salo at nubile auction, and unless\npayment la made before, will be sold\non Thursday, August (5, 190S. at 1 :30\no'clock p. m.. to pay tho delinquent as\nsessment, together with the cost of ad\nvertising ami, expense of sale.\nC. li. OLIVER, Secretary.\nc75S I\nIN THE DISTRICT COURT OF THE\nThird Judicial district. In and for the\ncounty of Salt Lako, State of Utah.\nJ. E. Darmer. trustee, et al plaintiff,\nvs Saint Joe Mining company, a cor\nporation, defendant; Ellen Garcy et al.,\nInlervcnors; A. T. Moon, receiver. No\ntice. Notice Is hereby given, that tho under\nsigned. A. T. Moon, tho duly-appointed,\nqualified and acting receiver of tho Saint\n.Too Mining company, by virtue of an or\nder of the District court of the Third\nJudicial district, in and for the county of\nSalt Lake. State of Utah, which said or\nder is dated tho 23rd day of May. A. D.\n190S. will at the hour of 12 o'clock noon\non Monday, the 29th day of June, A. D.\n190S, at the west entrance to the City\nand County building. In Salt Lake City,\nin said county and State, offer for sale\nand sell to tho highest and best bidder\nfor cash all tho property, both real and\npersonal, of the Saint Joe Mining com\npany, a corporation, said property being\ndescribed as follows, to wit:\nReal Estate Patented mining claims,\nsituated In West Mountain mining dis\ntrict. Salt Lako county, Utah.\n\"Mute No. 2.\" lot -HS4: \"Mute No. 1.\"\nlot 37C9; \"Uhllg No. 1.\" lot 3CS3; \"Uhllg\nNo. 2.\" lot 3CSI; \"Uhllg No. lot 4025;\n\"Ida.\" lot 39SS; \"Saint .Too No. l,\" lot\n4193: \"Mary Ann.\" lot 5007; \"Comet No.\n1.\" lot 5051: \"Rexlte.\" lot 39S9; \"Comet,\"\nlot 3991; \"Rainbow.\" lot 3992: \"Evening\nStar.\" lot 429G: \"R. A.\" lot 39S7; \"King\nBluchcr.\" lot 500S: \"Uhllg No. 5,\" lot\n5050; \"Owl.\" lot 5052.\nUNPATENTED CLAIMS.\n\"Comet No. 2\" and \"Butternut\" lodo\nmining claims, situate In the West\nMountain mining district. Salt Lako\ncounty, Utah.\nTogether with all buildings and fixtures\non said described real estate, consisting\nof 2 boarding houses, 2 cabins. 2 black\nsmith shops, bunkhousc. barn, chicken\nhouse, coal bins, etc., 2 boilers, engine. 2\ncompressors. 1 feed pump, water tank,\nforge, etc.\nPERSONAL PROPERTY.\nTwo Ingcrsoll drills, 1 Leyner drill, drill\nsteel, timbers. lumber, household furni\nture, blacksmith tools and supplies, gaso\nline engine, picks, shovels and miscel\nlaneous mine supplies.\nCertificate No. 34 for 10,665 shares of\ntho capital stock of the National Mining\ncompany. 1 safe. 2 typewriters and mis\ncellaneous office supplies. For a detailed I\nlist of the personal property ronsult tho\nreceiver, or examine the receiver's first\nreport, on fllo In raid entitled action.\nTerms of sale Cash, five thousand dol\nlars to be paid on day of sale and balance\non the entry of an order by said court\nconfirming such sale. No bid of less than\nfive thousand dollars to be accepted.\nAll property sold subject to right of re\ndemption as provided by law In case of\nmortgage foreclosures on real estat